  "issue_number": 11,
  "issue_title": "DevServerWrapper leaks env vars and unregistered shutdown hooks back into the build process when start() fails",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\n`DevServerWrapper.start()` performs three mutating actions on the host build JVM \u2014 captures the current env, installs `propagateEnv`, unregisters the build system's shutdown hooks \u2014 before calling `server.start()`. If anything after the env capture throws (port already in use, broken main class, hook init failure, classloader issue), none of the captured state is restored. The build process (sbt REPL, Gradle daemon, mill worker) is left with:\n\n- the application's `propagateEnv` permanently merged into its environment,\n- its own shutdown hooks gone (so it won't clean up on exit),\n- and on a subsequent retry, the corrupted state is snapshotted as the new \"initial\" \u2014 making the leak permanent for the session.\n\nA second, related failure: if `close()` is ever called without a successful prior `start()` (or after a `start()` that threw before the captures completed), `Environment.setEnv(null)` NPEs in the for-each on a null map, and `new IdentityHashMap<>(null)` NPEs at the copy-constructor.\n\n## Repro\n\nIn an sbt project using the plugin, set `liveServerType := HttpServerType` and configure `livePropagateEnv` with a marker like `MY_LEAK_CHECK -> \"1\"`. Make the underlying app fail to boot (e.g. occupy `live.reload.proxy.http.port` from another process). Then in the same sbt session:\n\n1. Run `liveReload` \u2014 it errors out.\n2. Run `eval sys.env.get(\"MY_LEAK_CHECK\")` \u2014 observe `Some(\"1\")`, even though the dev server never came up.\n3. Inspect registered shutdown hooks via reflection \u2014 sbt's are missing.\n\n## Root cause\n\n`core/runner/src/main/java/me/seroperson/reload/live/runner/DevServerWrapper.java`:\n\n```java\npublic void start() {\n  this.initialEnv = new HashMap<>(System.getenv());\n  Environment.putEnv(params.getPropagateEnv());           // \u2460 mutates env\n\n  this.buildSystemShutdownHooks = new IdentityHashMap<>(ShutdownHook.getRegistredShutdownHooks());\n  this.buildSystemHookThreadIds = ...;\n  ShutdownHook.unregisterShutdownHooks(buildSystemHookThreadIds);   // \u2461 removes hooks\n\n  server.start();                                                    // \u2462 may throw\n}\n```\n\nThere is no try/catch around \u2461/\u2462, so a throw from `server.start()` skips the restore step done in `close()`. `DevServerRunner.runBackground` swallows the throwable, logs it, and rethrows as a `RuntimeException` \u2014 it never gets a `wrapper` reference back (the wrapper variable was never returned), so nothing else can call `close()` either.\n\n`close()` itself unconditionally dereferences `initialEnv` and `buildSystemShutdownHooks`, so calling it on a never-started wrapper NPEs.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\n1. **`DevServerWrapper.start()`** \u2014 capture state into locals first, then wrap the three mutating steps in `try { ... } catch (Throwable t) { restore(); try { server.close(); } catch (Throwable ce) { t.addSuppressed(ce); } throw t; }`. Add a `started` `AtomicBoolean` so accidental double-start/restore is a no-op.\n2. **`DevServerWrapper.close()`** \u2014 null-guard both restore paths and null them out after restoring (idempotent).\n3. **`DevServerRunner.runBackground` catch block** \u2014 if `server` was constructed but `wrapper.start()` threw, attempt `server.close()` so proxy ports / xnio workers are released.\n4. Unit test in `core/runner/src/test/...` (new test directory) using a stub `ReloadableServer` whose `start()` throws, asserting env + shutdown hooks match the pre-call snapshot.\n\nEstimated diff: ~30 lines in `DevServerWrapper.java`, ~6 lines in `DevServerRunner.java`, ~40-60 lines for a new `DevServerWrapperTest.java`. Total ~75-95 lines.\n\n## Impact\n\nUser-visible across all three plugins (sbt/gradle/mill). The corruption is silent \u2014 env-var leakage shows up as mysterious behavior in subsequent build tasks, and the missing build-system shutdown hooks turn into \"Gradle daemon didn't release file handles\" / \"sbt left a lockfile\" complaints with no obvious cause.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n_No response_\n\n### Operating system\n\nLinux\n\n### Build System\n\nsbt\n\n### Version of jvm-live-reload\n\n0.1.1\n\n### JDK Version\n\n17.0.18\n\n### Extra context or search terms\n\n_No response_",
